Modeling California Housing Markets using Multiple Linear Regression

Joshua Zhong

12/28/2023

1 Abstract

This statistical report explores the dynamics of California house prices, utilizing a modified version of the California Housing data set derived from the 1990 census data. Employing methodologies such as K-means clustering, Box-Cox transformations, and bootstrapping, this analysis aims to uncover nuanced patterns and relationships within this housing market.

Key predictors that were analyzed spanned geographical location, housing characteristics, demographic details, and economic indicators of US Census block groups (i.e.neighborhoods grouped by the Census Bureau that will act as our observational unit ) and their inhabitants.

2 Introduction

2.1 Motivation

Understanding the dynamics influencing Californias house prices is essential due to its significant impact on the states economy. Housing affordability and market trends are critical concerns for residents, policymakers, and real estate professionals. This analysis aims to uncover the factors that shape housing prices across diverse census block groups, providing actionable insights for informed decision-making. By applying advanced statistical techniques such as Box-Cox transformations and bootstrapping, this study addresses data challenges and enhances the robustness and accuracy of findings. Utilizing the 1990 California census data offers a historical perspective, enriching our understanding of the socio-economic and spatial factors shaping the housing landscape over time.

2.2 Data set Description

The data set was found on Kaggle. It includes information gathered from various block groups in California during the 1990 Census. The U.S. Census Bureau uses the block group as the smallest geographical unit, typically consisting of 600 to 3000 people. Each observation in the data set represents one block group and comprises an average of 1425.5 individuals in a geographically compact area.

The data set contains 20640 observations of 9 dependent variables and one independent variable: median house value. The link to the raw CSV file in posted on GitHub: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JZhong01/STA321/main/Topic%203/ca-housing-price.csv.

  • Longitude(X1): How far west block group is located from prime meridian
  • Latitude(X2): How far north block group is located from equator
  • HousingMedianAge(X3): Median age of house within block group
  • TotalRooms(X4): Total number of rooms in block
  • TotalBedrooms(X5): Total number of bedrooms in block
  • Population(X6): Total number of residents in block group
  • Households(X7): Total number of households, defined as a group of people residing within a home unit
  • MedianIncome(X8): Median income, in thousands of US Dollars, for households within a block group
  • MedianHouseValue(Y): Median house value, in US Dollars, in a block
  • OceanProximity(X9): Location of the house to an ocean or sea, displayed as a categorical variable

2.3 Research Question

The primary objective of this analysis is to identify the main factors influencing house prices among California census block groups. This research aims to explore the following practical questions:

  • Which socioeconomic factors exhibit the strongest correlation with median house prices?
  • What data transformations, if any, are necessary for accurate modeling?

This analysis will seek to explore 2 hypotheses:

  • Hypothesis 1: A reduced model will perform better than the full model.

  • Hypothesis 2: Distance to the ocean is negatively correlated with median house value.

3 Methods

This section outlines the key methodologies employed in the analysis, including multiple linear regression, K-means clustering, Box-Cox transformation, and bootstrapping.

3.1 Multiple Linear Regression

Multiple linear regression (MLR) is used to examine how predictors such as housing characteristics and demographic factors influence California house prices. The dependent variable is MedianHouseValue, with independent variables including median income, population, and geographic location. The initial model includes all predictors to establish a baseline before refining based on diagnostics. Key assumptions are linearity, independence of observations, homoscedasticity, and normally distributed residuals.

3.2 K-means Clustering

To capture the geographical variation of latitude and longitude in a more interpretable and meaningful way, K-means clustering is employed. This method groups Californias block groups into distinct geographic regions, which are used as a new categorical variable, GeoCluster. T his clustering technique allows for latitude and longitude to be useful predictors, as considering them as separate predictors is unreliable. An elbow plot is employed to determine the optimal number of clusters. The main assumption is that geographic proximity (as measured by distance) meaningfully influences house prices, and that the number of clusters adequately represents regional differences.

3.3 Box-Cox Transformation

Box-Cox transformation is employed to address violations of regression assumptions, particularly non-normality and heteroscedasticity of residuals. By transforming the dependent variable, MedianHouseValue, the Box-Cox method helps stabilize variance and approximate a normal distribution of residuals, improving the overall fit of the regression model. This transformation assumes that the relationship between the predictors and the dependent variable can be linearized and that the response variable is strictly positive, which holds true in this dataset.

3.4 Bootstrap Residuals

Bootstrapping is used to generate robust confidence intervals for the regression coefficients, especially when the assumptions of normality for residuals are violated. By resampling the dataset 1,000 times with replacement, we estimate the variability in the coefficients without relying on parametric assumptions. Bootstrapping is a flexible, non-parametric approach, with the key assumption being that the sample is representative of the population, and resampling can approximate the true sampling distribution of the model estimates.

3.5 Other Methods

In addition to the core methods listed above, other statistical techniques may be employed, depending on the results of the initial analyses:

  1. Variance Inflation Factor (VIF): This will be used to detect multicollinearity in the multiple regression models.

  2. Residual Diagnostics: Standard diagnostic plots (Q-Q plot, residuals vs.fitted, etc.) will be used to assess the validity of assumptions in the regression model.

  3. Cross-Validation: If beneficial, cross-validation may be used to validate the robustness of the final model and prevent overfitting.

4.3.1 Creating Geographic Clusters

Before clustering longitude and latitude, well create an elbow plot to help determine the optimal number of clusters.

The plot graphs the total within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS), which measures the compactness of the clusters. As the number of clusters increases, the WCSS decreases because the data points are closer to the centroids of their respective clusters. Finding this elbow allows for us to choose a K that appropriately balances model complexity and cluster compactness.

set.seed(123)

# Subset the data to include only latitude and longitude
geo_data <- cahouses[, c('longitude', 'latitude')]

# Set a range of potential K values (number of clusters)
wcss <- numeric()  # Initialize an empty vector for within-cluster sum of squares

# Calculate WCSS for different numbers of clusters
for (k in 1:10) {
  kmeans_result <- kmeans(geo_data, centers = k)
  wcss[k] <- sum(kmeans_result$tot.withinss)  # Store the WCSS for each K
}

# Create the elbow plot
elbow_plot <- data.frame(K = 1:10, WCSS = wcss)

ggplot(elbow_plot, aes(x = K, y = WCSS)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +
  geom_point(color = "red", size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Elbow Plot for Optimal Number of Clusters", 
       x = "Number of Clusters (K)", 
       y = "Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS)") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1, 10, by = 1)) +  # Ensure whole numbers on x-axis
  ylim(0, 50000) +  # Adjust to fit WCSS scale better
  theme_minimal()

Based off the elbow plot, the optimal number of clusters is k=4 clusters. These clusters were then visualized and added as a new categorical variable, GeoCluster.


# Clustering longitude and latitude into regions using k-means
set.seed(123) # Setting a seed for reproducibility
kmeans_result <- kmeans(cahouses[, c('longitude', 'latitude')], centers = 4)

# Add the cluster assignment as a new categorical variable
cahouses$GeoCluster <- as.factor(kmeans_result$cluster)

# Summarize the clustering result
table(cahouses$GeoCluster)
## 
##     1     2     3     4 
##  1771  6743 10913  1006

# Plot the geographic clusters
ggplot(cahouses, aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, color = GeoCluster)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
  labs(title = "K-Means Clustering of Longitude and Latitude", 
       x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude") +
  theme_minimal()

4.3.2 Ocean proximity

OceanProximity describes whether the house is near the ocean. This is a critical factor when considering housing prices due to its strong association with real estate value.

Histograms for median house value across different levels of OceanProximity are plotted to visually investigate for any meaningful distributional differences.

par(mfrow = c(1,1))

hist(island$median_house_value, xlab = "Median House Value", main = "ISLAND" )

Upon reviewing these histograms, they all display a distinct right skew. To ensure that the different factor levels of OceanProximity are statistically significant from one another, ANOVA is run.

anova_model <- aov(median_house_value ~ ocean_proximity, data = cahouses)
summary(anova_model)
##                    Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## ocean_proximity     4 6.479e+13 1.620e+13    1595 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals       20428 2.075e+14 1.016e+10                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The Anova resulted in F(4, 20428) = 1595, p < 0.001. This means that at least one factor level differs from the others. As a result, OceanProximity is still relevant to the study at hand.

4.3.3 Chi-Squared Test between GeoCluster and OceanProximity

To ensure that the GeoCluster and OceanProximity variables are not confounding each other, a Chi-Squared Test of Independence is run. This test will check if there is an association between the two categorical variables. If the p-value is significant, we will need to assess the impact of using both variables in the model.

geo_ocean_table <- table(cahouses$GeoCluster, cahouses$ocean_proximity)
chisq.test(geo_ocean_table)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  geo_ocean_table
## X-squared = 9684.5, df = 12, p-value < 2.2e-16

Since ^2(12) = 9684.5, p < 0.01 from the chi-squared test of independence, there appears to be an association between geographic cluster and ocean proximity. This concern will be addressed when candidate models are built.

4.6 Multicollinearity and Variable Selection

Multicollinearity occurs when two or more predictor variables in a model are highly correlated, which can obscure the true relationship between each predictor and the response variable. A key step before building the regression model is to check for multicollinearity among the numerical variables.

4.6.1 Pairwise Scatterplot

A pairwise scatterplot is used to visually inspect the relationships between numerical variables and check for highly correlated pairs. The correlation coefficients between the variables are shown on the plot, and higher correlations indicate potential issues with multicollinearity.


pairs.panels(cahouses[, -c(1, 2, 9, 10, 11)], pch=21, main="Pair-wise Scatter Plot of Numerical Variables")

Visually, the pairwise scatterplot reveals a few concerning cases of collinearity. For instance, the correlation between the number of rooms and the number of bedrooms is extremely high (0.98), suggesting these two variables are capturing very similar information. Other large correlations exist between population and households (0.91), and rooms with households (0.92). These strong correlations indicate multicollinearity, which may distort our regression results. In the next section, we formally test for multicollinearity using the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF).

4.6.2 Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) Check

VIF values were calculated to formally detect multicollinearity.


full_model <- lm(median_house_value~. - longitude - latitude, data = cahouses)
vif(full_model)
##                         GVIF Df GVIF^(1/(2*Df))

In examining the VIF values, Total Rooms (VIF = 12.97), Total Bedrooms (VIF = 36.05), and Households (VIF = 34.57) exhibit extremely high multicollinearity, which is consistent with our earlier visual inspection of the pairwise scatterplots. These VIF values for total rooms, total bedrooms, and households suggest multicollinearity. These issues will be addressed in the variable selection and modeling steps.

5 Regression Modeling

After performing the exploratory data analysis and preparing the data, the next step is to develop a regression model. The aim is to build a model that not only meets statistical requirements, such as satisfying assumptions about linearity, normality, and homoscedasticity, but also provides valuable practical insights for decision-making.

Categorical variables with more than 2 factor levels results in the creation of dummy variables. This means the coefficients for the dummy variables compare each category to their respective baseline. In this study, Ocean_proximity has a baseline of INLAND and GeoCluster has a baseline of the first Cluster (North California).


cahouses$ocean_proximity <- as.factor(cahouses$ocean_proximity)
cahouses$ocean_proximity <- relevel(cahouses$ocean_proximity, ref = "INLAND")

5.3 Reduced Model

Both the original and alternate full models seem to experience many issues (one of which being multicollinearity). In order to alleviate this, well perform backwards stepwise regression on both.

5.3.1 Stepwise on Original Model


library(leaps)
library(caret)


# Define the control using a 10-fold cross-validation
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

# Define the grid of tuning parameters (number of predictors)
nvmaxGrid <- expand.grid(nvmax = seq(1, 13, by = 1))

# Set the seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Perform the backward stepwise regression with cross-validation
model.step <- train(median_house_value ~ . - latitude - longitude,
                    data = cahouses,
                    method = "leapBackward",
                    trControl = fitControl,
                    tuneGrid = nvmaxGrid) 

# Display the results
print(model.step)

Using 10-fold CV, we see that the optimal number of predictors is p = 13, which means no variables were removed in the stepwise model. This isnt particularly helpful as it is the same as the original full model. As a result, we choose to disqualify this model from our candidate models.

5.3.2 Stepwise on Alternate Model

In our alternate model, we replace GeoCluster and OceanProximity with numeric variables that are measuring the distance to the the coast and 4 major Californian cities.



# Define the control using a 10-fold cross-validation
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

# Define the grid of tuning parameters (number of predictors)
nvmaxGrid <- expand.grid(nvmax = seq(1, 9, by = 1))

# Set the seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Perform the backward stepwise regression with cross-validation
alt.model.step <- train(median_house_value ~ . - GeoCluster,
                    data = final_merged_data,
                    method = "leapBackward",
                    trControl = fitControl,
                    tuneGrid = nvmaxGrid)

5.4 Box-Cox Transformation

Box-Cox transformations were conducted on both full models and the stepwise model using merged data. We are using this as it normalizes the data and reduces heteroscedasticity.

5.4.1 Optimal Lambda

Using Box-Cox plots, we determine the optimal lambda for each of our models.


par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

# Box-Cox of Full Model (Original)
boxcox_full <- boxcox(median_house_value ~ . - longitude - latitude, data = cahouses, lambda = seq(0.10, 0.16, length = 10))
mtext("Box-Cox of Full Model (Original)", side = 3, line = 1, cex = 0.8)

# Box-Cox of Full Model (Alternate)
boxcox_alt <- boxcox(median_house_value ~ . , data = final_merged_data, lambda = seq(0.10, 0.16, length = 10))
mtext("Box-Cox of Full Model (Alternate)", side = 3, line = 1, cex = 0.8)

# Box-Cox of Reduced Model (Alternate)
boxcox_step_alt <- boxcox(median_house_value ~ . - GeoCluster - Distance_to_SanJose - Distance_to_SanDiego - households - total_rooms, data = final_merged_data, lambda = seq(0.10, 0.16, length = 10))
mtext("Box-Cox of Reduced Model (Alternate)", side = 3, line = 1, cex = 0.8)

Based off the plots, we determine that lambda is around 0.12 - 0.13. We will now transform our response variables to the power of our respective lambdas.

5.4.2 Applying Box-Cox Transformation


lambda_full <- 0.13
lambda_alt <- 0.125
lambda_step_alt <- 0.13


#Add transformed response variables

cahouses$transformed_house_value <- (cahouses$median_house_value^lambda_full - 1) / lambda_full

final_merged_data$alt_transformed_house_value <- (final_merged_data$median_house_value^lambda_alt - 1) / lambda_alt

final_merged_data$step_transformed_house_value <- (final_merged_data$median_house_value^lambda_step_alt - 1) / lambda_step_alt


#Refit models with transformed responses

boxcox_full_model <- lm(transformed_house_value ~ . - longitude - latitude - median_house_value, data = cahouses)

boxcox_alt_model <- lm(alt_transformed_house_value ~ . - step_transformed_house_value - median_house_value , data = final_merged_data)

boxcox_step_alt_model <- lm(step_transformed_house_value ~ . - GeoCluster - Distance_to_SanJose - Distance_to_SanDiego - households - total_rooms - median_house_value - alt_transformed_house_value, data = final_merged_data)

6 Evaluating Candidate Models

To evaluate the candidate models, we will assess their performance using various goodness-of-fit metrics, including the Adjusted R-squared, AIC (Akaike Information Criterion), BIC (Bayesian Information Criterion), and RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error). Additionally, well validate the models and check for assumptions.

6.1 Goodness of Fit Measures

Goodness-of-fit measures help us understand how well our models capture the variability in the data. Here are the results for the candidate models:



select=function(m){ # m is an object: model
 e = m$resid                           # residuals
 n0 = length(e)                        # sample size
 SSE=(m$df)*(summary(m)$sigma)^2       # sum of squared error
 R.sq=summary(m)$r.squared             # Coefficient of determination: R square!
 R.adj=summary(m)$adj.r                # Adjusted R square
 MSE=(summary(m)$sigma)^2              # square error
 Cp=(SSE/MSE)-(n0-2*(n0-m$df))         # Mellow's p
 AIC=n0*log(SSE)-n0*log(n0)+2*(n0-m$df)          # Akaike information criterion
 SBC=n0*log(SSE)-n0*log(n0)+(log(n0))*(n0-m$df)  # Schwarz Bayesian Information criterion
 X=model.matrix(m)                     # design matrix of the model
 H=X%*%solve(t(X)%*%X)%*%t(X)          # hat matrix
 d=e/(1-diag(H))
 PRESS=t(d)%*%d   # predicted residual error sum of squares (PRESS)- a cross-validation measure
 tbl = as.data.frame(cbind(SSE=SSE, R.sq=R.sq, R.adj = R.adj, Cp = Cp, AIC = AIC, SBC = SBC, PRD = PRESS))
 names(tbl)=c("SSE", "R.sq", "R.adj", "Cp", "AIC", "SBC", "PRESS")
 tbl = round(tbl, 2)
 tbl
 }




output <- rbind(select(full_model), select(full_merged_model), select(fstep_alt_model), select(boxcox_full_model), select(boxcox_alt_model), select(boxcox_step_alt_model))

6.2 Multicollinearity Consideration

However, it is important to note that the Box-Cox Full Alternate model may suffer from multicollinearity. Multicollinearity implies that while the model as a whole may predict well, interpreting individual coefficients can be problematic due to high correlations between the predictor variables. This can lead to unstable estimates and make it difficult to understand the effect of each variable independently.

To address this, if we prioritize a more parsimonious model that mitigates multicollinearity, the Box-Cox Stepwise Alternate model would be a better choice. This model simplifies the predictor set, making it easier to interpret the coefficients individually.

7 Conclusion

7.1 Main Findings

The findings of our analysis indicate that the original full model had significant issues with linearity and constant variance, which were mitigated by the application of a Box-Cox transformation. Various transformations and model adjustments were considered, and the Box-Cox Full Alternate model was ultimately selected as the best balance between statistical and practical significance. This model was found to have all predictor variables statistically significant at the 0.05 significance level, and the robustness of these findings was confirmed through traditional inferential statistics. Therefore, this model is recommended for predicting median house values in California homes within the context of US Census Bureau block groups.

7.2 Drawbacks and Future Improvements

While the Box-Cox Full Alternate model addresses many of the issues present in the original model, it comes with several limitations:

  • Multicollinearity: The model exhibits a staggeringly high multicollinearity, which can inflate standard errors and lead to unreliable estimates for regression coefficients. Addressing multicollinearity through techniques like ridge regression or principal component analysis could enhance the models reliability.

  • Interpretability of Coefficients: The coefficients of the Box-Cox transformed model are more challenging to interpret compared to models using untransformed data. Future work could explore partial transformations or alternative methods to improve interpretability without sacrificing model performance.

  • Model Complexity and Interactions: The simplification of the model to improve interpretability meant that potential interactions between variables were not thoroughly analyzed. Future models could include interaction terms to capture more complex relationships between predictors.

  • Predictive Power: Although the Box-Cox Full Alternate model achieved the best PRESS score, indicating good goodness of fit, we did not use cross-validation or extensive bootstrapping to thoroughly evaluate its robustness. Implementing these techniques in future analyses could provide a more comprehensive assessment of the models predictive power and its generalizability to new data.

7.3 Applications of Final Model

The Box-Cox Full Alternate model is useful for predicting housing prices in California based on the 1990 US Census data. This model can serve as a benchmark for future census results in California, allowing for comparative time series analysis to evaluate the evolving impact of certain predictors on housing prices over time.

However, it is recommended that this model be used with caution due to minor violations of regression assumptions. While bootstrap methods and transformations have addressed some of these issues, the model may still be less accurate at the extremes of the data. Additionally, the discretization of the underlying data before analysis could impact the results and should be considered in future applications.

Future research could focus on addressing the limitations identified in this study. Techniques such as ridge regression to mitigate multicollinearity, exploring alternative transformations to improve coefficient interpretability, and incorporating interaction terms for a more comprehensive model are potential avenues for improvement. By continuously refining the model, its predictive accuracy and practical applicability can be enhanced, providing valuable insights into the factors influencing housing prices in California.
